# TypeScript Standards

## Types

- All shared types live in `.utils/types/index.ts` — never scatter type definitions.
- Derive types from Zod schemas: `type Foo = z.infer<typeof FooSchema>`.
- Use `type` for plain shapes, `interface` for extensible contracts.
- Never use `any`. Use `unknown` + type guard for truly unknown shapes.
- Strict mode enabled
- Define interfaces for all props, API responses, and domain models
- Use type inference where obvious, explicit types where helpful
- Prefer explicit domain types for `OrganizationRole`, `DocumentStatus`, `NotificationKind`, and similar shared concepts instead of stringly-typed literals scattered across files

```ts
// ❌ BAD
function process(data: any) { return data.value; }

// ✅ GOOD
function process(data: unknown): string {
  if (typeof data === "object" && data !== null && "value" in data) {
    return String((data as { value: unknown }).value);
  }
  throw new TypeError("Invalid data shape");
}
```

## Error Handling

- Never swallow errors with empty `catch` blocks.
- Always log context alongside the error.

```ts
// ❌ BAD
try { await fetchData(); } catch (e) {}

// ✅ GOOD
try {
  await fetchData();
} catch (error) {
  console.error("fetchData failed", { error });
  throw error;
}
```

## Naming

- `camelCase` for variables and functions.
- `PascalCase` for types, interfaces, classes, and components.
- `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` for true constants.
- Prefix booleans: `is`, `has`, `can`, `should`.
